This paper is primarily focused on the performance of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) in image recognition tasks, which falls under the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. The paper also discusses the role of learning and classification strategies, which could be relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper includes a psychophysical study involving human observers, which could be relevant to the human-computer interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of a standard architecture (ResNet-50) and the potential for improved object detection performance, which could be relevant to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category.
